@deathcap wrapping your client listener in a 'state' listener only works if you remove all previous listeners on each state change. E.G.

```javascript
client.on('state', function(newState, oldState) {
  if (newState === states.HANDSHAKE) {
    client.on(0x00, handleHandshake);
  }
  else if (newState === states.LOGIN) {
    client.removeListener(0x00, handleHandshake);
    client.on(0x00, handleLoginStart);
    client.on(0x01, handleEncryptionResponse);
  }
  // etc...
});
```
Messy stuff. It really only works for the checking when we reach the states.PLAY. This is the proper way to convert them

```javascript
client.on([states.PLAY, 0x04], function(packet) {
  // do stuff
});
// is the same as
client.on(0x04, function(packet) {
  if (client.state !== states.PLAY) return;
  // do stuff
});
```

@roblabla But for `once()` (as used in test.js `serverClient.once([state, packetId], function(receivedPacket)`).. the specified function only executes one time, so if the state comparison fails and returns immediately, then the function would have already executed so it wouldn't be called against on the next, desired, state change right? Experimented a bit with re-adding the listener before returning, but couldn't come up with a clean solution. Maybe you can :)

Removing the removal of [state,packet] events for now in this PR, probably best handled separately, don't want to get too bogged down in this one (but all the original commits remain available at https://github.com/deathcap/node-minecraft-protocol/commits/feature-packetnames-dev for reference). 

@superjoe30 Squashed all the commits, any other changes needed?

Well, for future reference, client.once can be transformed into

```javascript
client.once(0x03, function onChat(data) {
  if (client.state !== states.PLAY) {
    client.once(onChat);
    return;
  }
  // do stuff
});
```

Not very pretty I give you that. That's why I didn't want to remove the [state, packetId] before we get named packets ^^.
